Iowa State wanted someone other than Jamie
Carey and Heather Schreiber shooting for No. 11 Texas. So Nina
Norman and Tai Dillard obliged.
article.headline: Freshman Norman scores season-high 19 points in win
article.linkText: Texas wins rare game at Iowa State
article.story:
AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Iowa State wanted someone other than Jamie Carey and Heather Schreiber shooting for No. 11 Texas. So Nina Norman and Tai Dillard obliged.

	   Norman, a freshman, scored a season-high 19 points and Dillard
had 16 as Texas won at Iowa State for the first time in four tries, beating the Cyclones 65-55 Saturday.

	   The two came through in a big way while Iowa State played a
triangle-and-two to try to slow Carey and Schreiber.

	   "I had a girl kind of one-on-one, but she wasn't really
guarding me, so I kept shooting the jumper,'' Norman said.

	   When a reporter suggested that must have been a nice situation,
Norman smiled.

	   "Yeah, it was nice,'' she agreed. "I don't get that too
often.''

	   Norman, a 35 percent shooter, shot 8-for-12 in topping her
previous best of 12 points. Dillard, shooting 37.6 percent for the
season, finished 8-of-14.

	   Stacy Stephens added 17 points and 13 rebounds for the Longhorns
(17-5, 10-1 Big 12), who led by six early in the second half, fell behind by six, then ran off 10 straight points to go ahead.

	   Stephens helped Texas to a 43-27 rebounding advantage and had
seven of her team's 12 offensive rebounds.

	   "I really thought Stacy Stephens was the difference in the
game,'' Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly said. "She manhandled us in
the second half. She got more offensive rebounds than our whole
team got.''

	   Schreiber, who had averaged 15.7 points over the last seven
games, was held to seven. Carey scored six, all on free throws in
the final minute.

	   "Obviously they did a great job on Heather and Jamie Carey,''
Texas coach Jody Conradt said. "Those are two of our most prolific
scorers and people we count on. But what you want to happen is for
somebody else to step up and (Norman) stepped up. I thought Tai
Dillard also did a good job.

	   "Both of them really made some key baskets and really kept us
in the game offensively.''

	   Iowa State (9-13, 4-7) got 22 points from Lindsey Wilson but
managed only one basket -- a layup by Wilson -- in the final 6:51.
The Cyclones' top three scorers, Wilson, Anne O'Neil and Lisa
Kriener, shot a combined 3-for-23 in the second half.

	   Iowa State still made it interesting, going on a 15-3 run to go
up 44-38 after trailing 35-29. Wilson, Mary Cofield and Brittany
Wilkins each made a 3-pointer in that stretch and Wilkins added a
baby hook. The 3-pointer was just the second of the season for
Wilkins, a 6-foot-3 redshirt freshman who was left alone at the top
of the key and knocked the shot down.

	   The Cyclones led 50-45 after Wilkins scored inside, but Texas
then took control. Norman made two jump shots, Stephens scored on
two putbacks and Dillard scored in transition after blocking
Wilson's shot, putting the Longhorns up 55-50.

	   Wilson's two free throws cut the lead to three, but Schreiber
followed up a missed shot to make it 57-52 with 2:51 left.

	   "We were up by six with eight minutes left, we were at home,
the crowd was into it, we were into it. We were definitely looking
to extend that,'' Wilson said. "They just made a game of it again
and before we knew it, we were down five.''

	   Iowa State had been called for only two fouls in the second half
and had to foul five times in 10 seconds to finally put Texas on
the free throw line. But the Longhorns made eight straight in the
final 51.4 seconds -- six by Carey and two by Norman -- to secure the
victory.
